=99ve taken your next turn, add 10 points to the first roll of that turn to=
 find out how much your spare is worth, and write that score on the previou=
s frame (the frame on which you got the spare).<sup id=3D"_ref-7" class=3D"=
reference trusted" aria-label=3D"Link to Reference 7"><a href=3D"https://ww=
w.wikihow.com/Score-Bowling#_note-7">[7]</a>
</sup> A spare can be worth anywhere from 10 to 20 points depending on how =
much you score in the next roll.<sup id=3D"_ref-8" class=3D"reference" aria=
-label=3D"Link to Reference 8"><a href=3D"https://www.wikihow.com/Score-Bow=
ling#_note-8">[8]</a>
</sup>
<ul>
<li>For example, let's say you scored 6 points in turn 1. In turn 2, you kn=
ock over 3 pins, then 7, for a spare. Wait until you've rolled the first ro=
ll of turn 3 to tally your score. Then if you roll a 7, add up 6 (from turn=
 1) +10 (your spare)+ 7 (your first roll of turn 3) to get 23!</li>
<li>After you=E2=80=99ve scored your spare, add up your rolls for turn 3. I=
f you rolled a 7 and then a 2, you'd add 23 (your score in turn 2) +9 to ge=
t 32 for turn 3.</li>
</ul>
</div>
